# 📦 Docker Images

Docker Image is a lightweight, read-only package containing everything required to run an application.

It includes:

- Application Code
- Runtime
- Libraries
- Dependencies
- Environment Variables
- Configuration Files

An image acts as a template for creating containers.

Dockerfile
      │
      ▼
Docker Image
      │
      ▼
Docker Container


# 📄 Dockerfile

A Dockerfile is a text file containing instructions used to build a Docker image.

Example:

Vi Dockerfile
FROM nginx:latest

COPY index.html /usr/share/nginx/html/

EXPOSE 80

CMD ["nginx","-g","daemon off;"]
save 

# Common Dockerfile Instructions

## FROM

Specifies the base image.

dockerfile
FROM nginx:latest
COPY
Copies files from the local machine into the image.
COPY index.html /usr/share/nginx/html/
EXPOSE
Documents which port the application uses.
EXPOSE 80
## CMD
Defines the default command executed when the container starts.
CMD ["nginx","-g","daemon off;"]
# 🏗 Building Docker Images

Docker reads the Dockerfile and creates an image.

docker build -t my-nginx:v1 .

Explanation

| Option       | Description                 |
|---------     |-------------                |
| docker build | Builds an image             |
| -t | Assigns image name and tag            |
| . | Current directory (Build Context)      |


# 🚀 Creating Docker Containers

Containers are created from Docker Images.

Docker Image

        │

docker run

        │

Docker Container

Example

docker run -d -p 80:80 --name nginx-container nginx:latest


# 🔍 Understanding the Command
docker run -d -p 80:80 --name nginx-container nginx:latest
```

| Option            | Meaning                             |
| docker run        | Creates and starts a container      |
| -d                | Runs container in detached mode     |
| -p                | Maps Host Port to Container Port    |
| 80:80             | Host Port → Container Port          |
| --name            | Assigns a custom container name     |
| nginx:latest      | Image used to create the container  |

